TUSKEGEE Two Negroes de-
feated white incumbents In run
off city election for council seats.


Rev. K. l.. Buford, civil
rights leader, and DR.. Stanley
Smith, a faculty member of Tus-
kegee Institute, defeated two men
running for the second term.


The new council will have three
white members and two Negr oes.


1t is the first time since re-
construction days after the civil
war that Negroes have won any
public office in an Alabama
election.

2 NEGROES win
SEATS IN ALABAMA

McCOMB, Miss. Negro civil
rights leaders have asked Presi-
dent Johns on and Gov. Paul John
son declare martial law inthe city
where Negro homes and churches
have been bombed recently.


Aaron Henry, state president of
the National ASS ociation for the
Advancement of Colored People
reported that three more homes
were bombed last week. He said
Pike County needs martial law
to protect the lives Of people.


Pike County Sheriff R. R. War
rem stated the explosions we're
peculiar and he thought they we're
started to get the federalg govern
ment to declare martial law.

Negroes Want
Martial Law

Whitney M. Young, Jr.. exc
cutive director of the National
Urban League will be the speak
er for the 10th Anniversary Gel
ebration of the Phoenix Urban
League on Monday, October S,
at the Westward Ho Hotel in
Phoenix.


Young is recognized as one of
the countrys most dynamic and
effective leaders in interracial
relations. The St. Louis Post
Dispatch has said that he "...
has put the National Urban League
in the forefront of those who are
urging special compensatory
programs to make up for the
disadvantage American Negroes
have suffered for so manyyears.


He also has brought a new
sense of urgency to the League.
Perhaps the most pr OCCASIONAL
but least demonstrative of civil
rights groups, the 54-year-old
organization specializes in job
training and social welfare"

HEAD TO APPEAR

DETROIT Rev. jill. Jackson.
pastor of Olivet Baptist Church
of Chicago, was reelected presi-
dent of the National Baptist Con-
vention for the twelfth conse-
cutive term.


DR.. Jackson. 60, head the lar
gest religious group of Negroes
in America. His group num-
Der more than S million.


A fund of $40 million was es-
tablished to provide education
for deserving young students.
Baptist Reflect Prexy

DR.. SIM. Chapman. dentist. has
opened his office at 1917 E. Wash
ington, the former office of the
late DR.. Robert B. Phillips.


A native of Louisiana. DR..
Chapman practiced dentistry
there for l3 years before moving
to the city this summer. He is
a graduate of Meharry Medical
College and he served in the
armed forces.


He is a member of the Phi
Beta Sigma fraternity and the
American Legion.


His wife, Pauline, is his dental
assistant.


The Chapman have three
daughters Greta. Delano. and
Pamela, and one son, Gregory.

PARIS Sugar Ray Robinson,
former world middleweight box
ing champion. has been named
the French sports writer's most
popular foreign sports man to
visit France in 1864.


An aging Sugar won 10 round
disputed decision over Yoland
Leveque last week.


Robinson, A, has slowed down
and he is a poor image of his
former agile self.
SUGAR CITED

PHILADEL PHIA Wallace
Muhammad. son of Elijah
Muhammad, head of the Black
Muslims, has announced his de-
cision to move his headquarters
to Philadelphia.


Wallace said his father was old
and i'll and had lost his aims of
his group. Wallace is establish
ing a mosque and center under
his supervision in the City of
Brotherly Love.

The biggest and best fair of all
Arizona State Fairs will be
opened Nov. E when Miss Amer
lea, Arizona's Vonda Van Dyke,
cuts the ribbons. That day Of
ficially called Governors Day
will feature the traditional well
come address by Gov. Paul Fan
min.


Kids Day will also be held.
The first 5000 children will
enjoy free rides on the midway.


The Lennon Sisters, one of the
most famous trios in the nation,
will appear Nov. 6-l0.


Other featured performers in
clude Jack Incl. Freddy Morgan.
Bobby and Barbara, dance team.
Mel and Clora Bryant, the Tan
gier Acrobatic Troupe and many.
more.


There is room for 7 500 parked
cars and the exhibit space has
been increased.


Arizona State Fair is one of the
few state fairs where patrons can
view a free grandstand show
daily.


Other attractions include
Strong's Circus, Henry's
Chimps, Frazier's World Fair
rides and a huge midway.
Up, display their envelopes.

S. Williams, A, GIG S. 18th
Avenue, was booked on a homicide
charge Saturday for the fatal
shooting of Oscar Harvey. IS,
HOS w. Lincoln.


Williams and Harvey had been
drinking most of the day and
argued over a woman. Williams
shot him in the chest with a
Is gauge shotgun about 2 pm.
SHOTGUN DEATH

NEW YORK Comedian Dick
Gregory refused to continue as
the costar in a night club revue
with Frances Faye at Basin Street
East. He also denied that he
had called President Johnson
"suupid'' in his act.


The dispute started when both
stars wanted to give the final
act. which is always reserved
for the main feature.


Ralph Watkins, club manager,
reported he was not pleased with
Gregorys act. He didn't think
a night club stage should be used
as a "civil rights platform"
